SYMPTOM_TEXT: After my mother took the first vaccine shot on March 4th 2021, I noticed the changes 2 weeks later. Her handwriting became more disoriented in her checkbook. She said she had trouble remembering which week days to write in her checkbook. I noticed incomplete transaction lines. She forgot to take medications for the first time in years.  She used to be an early riser. She started to get up late in the mornings between 8 am and 9 am. She does not eat as much as she should. She drank coffee more frequently all day daily. She hardly drank enough water to avoid her chronic consciptation problem in the bathroom. She has not been herself lately since her first shot. So I have a good reason to be concerned. I think a 2nd vaccine shot is not really a good idea.
LAB_DATA: My mother and I went to see the doctor last Tuesday on March 23 2021 to discuss the decline of memory.  She forgot to take her medications for the first time in years after her first vaccine shot. She apparently passed the dementia exam so far.  I made the point to remind her to remember to take her medications each morning and drink enough water during meals and between meals if possible.
OTHER_MEDS: My mother has 2 prescriptions for thyroidism and a number of vitamins that are recommended but not required.

VFF, PERRLA, 4/4 strength in the biceps/triceps/hand grip/hamstrings/quads/plantar/dorsiflexion. SILT UE/LE. No pronator drift. Normal finger-nose-finger. Normal rapid alternating movements. Reflexes 2+ in the patella bilaterally. Normal gait. BP on the presentation was 226/111, pulse was 78, respiratory rate was 20, oral temperature was 36.8 degrees Celsius, and SpO2 was 99%. Denied COVID-19 symptoms, activity change, chills, fever, congestion or dental problems, discharge or itching of the eye, chest tightness, shortness of breath, stridor, chest pain, leg swelling, abdominal distention or pain, dysuria, frequency, arthralgias, joint swelling, color change or rash, dizziness, syncope, back or neck pain, weakness, N/V, HA, vision changes, confusion, bowel changes, behavioral problems or confusion. Has been taking medications as prescribed, no prior history of CVA. PMH of DM and HTN.
LAB_DATA: Labs 3/29/2021: BMP, troponin, prothrombin wnl. Calcium slightly elevated at 11.6. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was vaccinated around 10:55 AM. Within a couple of minutes she started feeling lightheaded, sweaty, and had blurry vision while sitting. She reported no history of blood sugar issues, but she said she only had some donut to eat today. I initially gave her three glucose tablets and a bottle of water, which she sipped. She reported feeling better within a few minutes. I checked her blood pressure at 10:59 AM. It read low at 81/44 with a pulse of 73. But, I checked again since I doubted the accuracy of the reading. The second reading was 101/56, with a pulse of 79. Patient said she was feeling better, but continued to sit. I gave her one more glucose tablet to equal a total of 16 g of carbs given. She sat for at least fifteen minutes until she felt well enough to get up and shop. She checked back after shopping and said she was fine.

Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine EUA Upon reconciliation of the patient records in ICARE, it was brought to the attention of Dr. that this patient, is only 17 years old, and was inadvertantly administered the Moderna vaccine.  Upon review, per the CDC website: https://www.cdc.gov/vaccines/covid-19/info-by-product/clinical-considerations.html if a minor is inadvertantly administered the vaccine, a second dose may be administered if the benefits outweight the risk.  Called patient today, spoke wtih mother Svetlana, to inform her of the inadvertant vaccine administration to her son such that he is 17 years old, which does not meet the EUA approved age of 18 years and older for Moderna.  Mother stated that son tolerated first dose well, and has no underlying health conditions.  Discussed the current lack of evidence/data for those less than 18 years old on the efficacy of the Moderna vaccine, but that trials are currently underway.  At this time discussed risk/benefts, and clinically at this time there is minimal risk to her son receiving the second dose if the parent/son agree.  Informed her that a parent/gaurdian must be present with her son at time of vaccination.  Mother verbalized and agreed to all above information. Mother stated that she will have her son get second dose, and to keep appt on 4/23.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 3/25: Approx 5 mins after injection, started breathing quickly and became lightheaded. Moments later, heart rate elevated north of 190 bpm and blood pressure went up to approx 180/100. Would race and then stabilize throughout the day/night. Extremely lethargic. No trouble breathing (was able to breathe and take deep breathes) but took effort to breathe.  3/27: 1:40A woke up heart began racing at close to 200 bpm. Dry mouth, shakes. Hospital did EKG, blood work and chest X-ray. all were normal, lungs were clear. However, glucose and bilirubin were both slightly elevated.  3/29: Still feeling lethargic. Heart rate has stabilized some but is still erratic. It  easily increases from simply walking around the house (much more than usual).   3/30: Scheduled appointment with primary care physician 3/31: Scheduled appointment with cardialogist
LAB_DATA: 3/25: ekg, blood labs - both communicated as normal 3/27: ekg, bloodwork, chest X-ray. Lungs clear, ekg communicated as normal, blood work normal (however glucose and bilirubin slightly elevated)

Upon the initial vaccination day (March 23rd) there was discomfort and scoreness hours after vaccines was received, but it was minimal. The next day (24th) the area became swollen and red and was sensitive to the touch. I took Tylenol and used an ice pack for a few hours and the area started to return to its normal status, with a slight indication of a ring forming around the area of injection. I continued to take Tylenol and use an ice back moderately through the day on the 25th. By that evening the soreness was gone and well as the discomfort. Saturday the 26th everything seemed fine and I had no cause for alarm. However, on the evening of March 26th, the area of injection started to itch and was slightly pink but no visible signs of inflammation. The morning of Sunday, the 27th the injection site had flared up similar to a bee sting with significant irritation.  The prior remedy of the ice pack provided temporary relief. Wile the pack was on the inflammation went down and the itching stopped, but after the affects for the cooling wore off the Injection area flared up again and turned a bright reddish-pink. Around 10 or 11am I took a double dose of claritine to relieve the itching within 20 minutes the subsiding and the injection area began to dull in color. That same evening I took a benadryl around 4 or 5 pm. I fell asleep due to thr medicaruon and upon waking the hives were gone and the area was a light pink. Prior to goong to bed thatvnight i took another Benadryl. Upon waking up monday the 29th the inflammatiin is no existant and the area is only red at the site of injection with a slight discloration where the area had inflammed. I continued taking Zrtec during the dau, as i was out of claritin. No irritarion.

Chills, mild headache, lowered oxygen levels to 85 SpO2.  Gone after 24 hours.  But this is episodic.  I don't recall when it happened again.  Same pattern and gone after 24 hours.    But on 3/22/2021,  it started in the evening and lasted for 36 hours.  This time the additional symptom of non-productive cough appeared for the first time.  COVID test during that same day (in anticipation of angiogram on the 24th) was negative.  Oxygen levels continued to be low while in hospital for angiogram which resulted in two stents being emplaced and the following day for a TEE to get a better look at the valve.  No chills or cough until evening of the 25th.  Chills lasted for 24 hours, but non-productive cough and low oxygen levels persist up through the present time (March 29th). 43 year old female with a past medical history significant for asthma, anxiety, DM, migraines, thyroid papillary carcinoma who is presenting to the ED with an allergic reaction. She received her COVID vaccination at 1700. At approximately 1715 she felt a lump in her throat. Shortly after she felt as if her tongue/lips were tingling/becoming swollen and then she developed nausea. No rash or abdominal pain. No dyspnea or chest pain. All symptoms are consistent with prior episodes of anaphylaxis. She has had anaphylaxis to vaccinations in the past but was advised by her allergist to get the COVID vaccine today.  On arrival patient is quite anxious. Vital signs are stable. Her tongue is enlarged/mildly edematous, additionally appreciated mild lip/perioral swelling. There is no stridor or wheezing, no evidence of respiratory distress. Given examination findings, symptom description, findings concerning for anaphylaxis. As such, epinephrine promptly administered as well as solumedrol, famotidine, and benadryl. Shortly after the epinephrine she endorsed improvement in her swelling, though during benadryl administration she endorsed a sudden onset of subjective throat swelling/felt as if she could not breathe. Patient was reassessed, no change in initial examination findings, within a few minutes she felt her symptoms improve without intervention.A short while later she again felt as if her throat swelling was worsening, as such epinephrine dose re administered.  Following a 2.5 hour period of observation she endorsed continued improvement in her allergic symptoms, requested discharge home though continued observation offered. A course of prednisone prescribed, patient already with epi pen.  Patient discharged home.

In March 29 at approximately 10:05am a patient was at my station prepared to get Covid -19 vaccine. After asking pt the appropriate questions prior to getting vaccine I wiped the pt arm with alcohol pad  and injected the needle in patient left deltoid muscle. When I injected the ?vaccine? I felt no pressure from the injection as I would have any other vaccine I had given in the past. I instantly pulled the needle  out and pulled back the plunger I observed no residue in the barrel from the vaccine. I then used the other syringe that was at my station that did have the appropriate dose of vaccine and injected the patient. I  did indeed feel the pressure that I was familiar with when giving the pt the vaccine. I am very confident that the syringe did not have any vaccine in it. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt seen in ophthalmology clinic 3/16/21 for evaluation of c/o bilateral vision loss and admitted to hospital for further evaluation and management based on their findings. She has known history of cataracts, macular thinning of the left eye and bilateral pseudophakia, but no recent vision issues. Pt states that approximately 3 to 4 days after getting her first COVID-19 vaccination (Pfizer) on 2/16/2021 she noted blurred vision in left eye and over the course of the next several days, started to have worsening blurring as well as darkening of her vision to the point where she was only able to see faint outlines of objects. Did also have some associated visual hallucinations with this. Seen in clinic (exact date unknown but sometime between 2/16/21 and 3/8/21) where a visual acuity exam was done, and no further evaluation was recommended. But pt had ongoing issues and was ultimately seen by ophthalmology on 3/8/21 and was then directed to the ED on 3/8/2021 for possible stroke evaluation. In the ED, CT of the brain was negative for acute stroke. MRI was advised, but patient declined during that ED visit and voiced preference to schedule outpatient, however, she was never able to make that appointment. On 3/9/21, pt received her second COVID-19 vaccine, and 1 to 2 days later, she developed the same symptoms in the right eye, though does not feel that her visual acuity decreased by as much in that eye as it had in the left eye. Pt also has had mild associated frontal headache since her first COVID-19 vaccination, but it responds readily to acetaminophen. Pt seen in ophthalmology clinic again on 3/16/21. At that appointment, she had a funduscopic exam which showed mild temporal pallor and ophthalmology felt that this is likely inflammation of the optic nerve or optic nerve sheath, likely secondary to retrobulbar optic neuritis versus perineuritis possibly triggered by recent vaccination. Request was made for admission to Hospital for further evaluation and management. Hospital Course (admitted 3/16/21 ? 3/22/21): MRI of the brain and orbits revealed optic neuritis. In consultation with neurology and neuro-ophthalmology the pt was started on a 5-day course of methylprednisolone 1 g IV daily. The pt noted improvement in her vision rapidly. Primary diagnosis at discharge was optic neuritis, possibly triggered by covid-19 vaccination.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Hard, red, hot, itchy lumps under the skin at the injection site, about three inches both directions - occurred about 17 hours after the injection. This was accompanied by about 10 hours of chills (no cycling to heat, just chills all day) and nausea. I take the regular flu vaccines every year and never had any reactions to them, so this came as a surprise to me. The first COVID19 (Moderna) injection caused no symptoms of any sort, not even a sore arm. This one caused this weird under-the-skin hot rash-like thing, which may have started in the night when I was asleep, but was clearly annoying by morning. Later that evening I took an antihistamine, which relieved all symptoms, including the nausea. And the following day I seemed to have an abundance of more energy, taking another long hike. I do want to note that I took an 11.4 mile climbing hike the day after my first  vaccine, and again, a long hike today, just a day and a half after the second.  Knowing my own body well, I would say this was a mild allergic reaction to some component in this vaccine, since it was ended with one single does of antihistamine.
LAB_DATA: None. I do not have a medical professional.

I understand this could be a sudden shift in menstrual cycle due to the very beginning  of Peri-menopause, but it is unusual and the combination of the two events were the driving reason to report.  I have seen on this system there is a small number of women who reported similar side effects.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: HPI:  Patient is a 45-year-old female who presents for evaluation after COVID-19 vaccine reaction.  Patient just received 1st vaccine this morning.  She was being observed in the vaccine clinic when she started to experience numbness all over her body and hives over the upper chest.  She was brought immediately to the emergency department for treatment.  Upon assessment, she is lying flat in the bed.  States she feels weird.  No difficulty swallowing, no difficulty breathing.  She is not itching.  She has no known allergies.  MEDICAL DECISION MAKING Upon arrival to the emergency department patient was immediately assessed at the bedside.  She was lying in the bed, eyes closed, appeared somnolent with answering questions.  She did have urticaria on the upper chest.  She was also tachycardic.  IV was established, she was treated with intramuscular epinephrine, IV Benadryl, famotidine, and Solu-Medrol.  Patient was observed in our emergency department for 3 hours and had complete resolution in her symptoms.  She was reassessed on multiple occasions during her emergency department stay and continued to show signs of improvement.  I do feel that she is safe for discharge home.  Recommend not getting COVID-19 vaccine in the future given her allergic reaction today.  Patient is in agreement with this plan, she was discharged home in improved condition. Medications EPINEPHrine anaphylaxis kit 0.3 mg (0.3 mg Intramuscular Given 3/26/21 0814) methylPREDNISolone sodium succinate (SOLU-Medrol) injection 125 mg (125 mg Intravenous Given 3/26/21 0818) famotidine (PEPCID) injection 20 mg (20 mg Intravenous Given 3/26/21 0818) diphenhydrAMINE (BENADRYL) injection 50 mg (50 mg Intravenous Given 3/26/21 0816) sodium chloride 0.9% bolus injection 1,000 mL (0 mL Intravenous Stopped 3/26/21 0948)   broke out in hives, heart started racing, went to ED where they treated her. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine  Around 4 in the afternoon I started getting more intense pain in left arm.  By 5 PM I was starting to get mild nerve pain in the same arm, and the pain had spread from my left arm to include my neck and upper shoulder.  By 8 PM the nerve pain was getting worse and the muscular pain had spread to 2 inches bellow my shoulder blade (concentrated on the left side) and included the aforementioned areas. At 11 PM I noticed that my sense of touch was altered on the left side of my body, and the nerve pain was steadily getting worse.  I could feel pressure but not fine discriminative touch, and had little reaction to touch (I usually have a lot of hypersensitivity, and react very strongly to the slightest amount of touch). I tried going to bed around 12:30 AM but was not able to fall asleep until after 5:30 AM because the nerve pain was so sever at this point.  Positional changes and ice did not help, and I ended up taking Advil at 5:15 because I couldn't deal with the pain anymore.  This dampened the pain enough that I was able to go to sleep at 5:30 AM. The nerve pain was a 8/10 and went down my ulna to my 4 and 5th fingers.  This was some of the worst pain I have experienced in years. I have some lingering nerve pain in that arm (as well as dampened sensory sensation on the left side), but it is not as bad as it was the night of the vaccine.
OTHER_MEDS: Levothyroxine (0.025 MG), Omeprazole (20 MG), Estarylla, Zertec, Juice Plus, Vitamin D

The next day my arm was a little sore,  nothing unusual. The following day I was a little tired again nothing unusual. The 3rd day ( Mar 29) all hell broke loose.   I got the hives all over the place, I could not stop sneezing . I've got a massive headache, and I can barely stay awake over an hour without taking a nap. I am absolutely miserable! SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had never been pregnant before and have been undergoing fertility treatments for about two and a half years (6 failed IUIs followed by 2 failed frozen embryo transfers via IVF).  I had my third frozen embryo transfer on 3/12, almost exactly the same time Alaska opened vaccine availability to anyone over the age of 16.  Our doctor?s advice along with everything we found online showed not much was known about the vaccine, but there was no firm reason to think there would be a problem with getting it in early pregnancy.  We also knew that being pregnant would mean higher likelihood of having severe symptoms if I got Covid-19, so I signed up for and was administered the first Moderna vaccine on the day of my first pregnancy test. 3/22 my beta HcG level came back at 72, confirming pregnancy.  As is standard, I was asked to come back three days later to confirm appropriate growth in those numbers.  By Thursday, March 25th my HcG level had fallen to 17, and by Monday, March 29th that level was less than 3. It?s impossible to know if the vaccine played a role in the early miscarriage, but I wanted to provide the data in case there are any trends or information can be learned from my experience.
LAB_DATA: 3/22 beta HcG 72 3/25 beta HcG 17 3/29 beta HcG <3
OTHER_MEDS: Prenatal vitamins, vitamin D, Estradiol, Endometrin, and Progesterone in Oil

Symptoms immediately post-vaccination were a heavy, sore arm that hurt to move for 2-3 days, extreme exhaustion and fatigue. Mild issues with dysautonomia and vestibular issues that are being investigated. Fine since that wore off. Today (March 29), one week from receiving my first dose, a strange rash broke out on my forearm. It does not seem to hurt or itch, but it is different from anything I've seen apart from a nasty bruise. It looks like broken blood vessels the size of tiny freckles in clusters all over my arm. It does look a bit like a histamine rash, which I get due to Mast Cell Activation Syndrome, but a typical MCAS rash for me is usually far more aggressive and obvious than this rash, or straight up hives or welts. The rash has lasted the entire day and hasn't faded, but isn't noticeable unless you are looking at my arm specifically. Nothing changed about my medications, my routine, or anything I put on my skin that could cause this. I will visit my doctor if it doesn't fade or gets worse. Currently I am not too concerned, but this rash does not look like any of the documented reactions to the Moderna vaccine that I have found online. I thought it best to report it.

Patient reported to immunizing technician before administration of vaccine that he had a history of fainting post-vaccination due to anxiety and nerve about needles. Pt stated that previously he had fainted immediately post-vaccination. After discussing patient's medical history the supervising pharmacist advised pt to stay in vaccination seat for direct observation for 10-15min. After about 10 minutes post-vaccination in observation period the pt alerted immunizing tech, "oh, its happening." The tech brought a wet paper towel and placed it on the back of patient's neck and pt replied, "oh, that feels good", then patient's head immediately dropped and he went out of consciousness. Pharmacist witnessed event and rushed over to support patient from falling off chair. Pharmacist was rubbing and patting patients back and chest, yelling his name to arouse him. Pharmacist directed tech to call code white and alert store manager. In total, the patient was approximately in and out of consciousness about 20 seconds. Pt responded to stimulus and recovered without other effects or injury. Patient was fully responsive and aware of event went he became conscious again. We offered him a cold water bottle and encouraged him to remove mask if it helped him to breath better. Pt was able to communicate with pharmacist about the sensations he had leading to the event where he described first tingling in his feet, than dissociation from body, where he felt like he was having a dream but could hear someone yelling at him. EMS arrived at the scene and performed vital check. Based on patient abnormal hypertension at scene and higher BMI, EMS offered to transport patient to the ED for further tests and observation but patient declined. Patient was accompanied by his emergency contact, his father (who also witnessed the events unfold).
LAB_DATA: EMS arrived at the scene and obtained patient vitals 3/29/2021
CUR_ILL: anxiety about needles, past history of fainting post-vaccination (per patient ~5-10 yrs ago)
PRIOR_VAX: Prior to vaccine administration, pt reported having fainted about 5 -10 years ago at Dr's office after vaccination.

My balance is significantly impacted - any head movement at all triggers vertigo and nausea. I am unable to drive - I can just manage to get to the bathroom and back holding on to objects. I attempted to contact my physician this morning and left a message but did not receive a return call
LAB_DATA: Epley maneuver worsened vertigo and nausea

Pt received the first of the two-series COVID vaccination at 1512. Once in observation area, pt became unresponsive shortly after sitting down. This provider was called over by staff to pt, which was noted to have become unresponsive while sitting in the chair. Pt remained in the chair, did not fall or injure self. Upon arrival to patient, he was noted to have severe diaphoresis, prominent pallor, with shallow, slow breathing, no cyanosis noted. His head initially fell back and head was aligned/adjusted to maintain an open airway. This provider was speaking to the pt and performed a sternal rub to elicit a response, pt remained unresponsive and with eyes closed. Pt remained in this state for approximately 10 seconds. Pt noted to suddenly have some muscular rigidity to arms and torso and in order to prevent injury upon possible onset of seizure activity, pt was lowered to the floor by this provider and RN . Once on the ground the pt was relaxed and opened his eyes. Pt was immediately verbally responsive and asked if he passed out. Pt was able to sit up and was assisted into the wheelchair. Pt moved to treatment area where vitals and blood glucose were obtained. (@1525 BG- 104 mg/dL, VS BP 116/72, HR bradycardic @51 bpm, O2 sat 95%).  Patient responses/speech was clear and pt was oriented to self, place, time and situation. Pt stated that he felt nauseated upon sitting in the observation area and admitted that he only had a coffee today, nothing to eat all day and attributed this as the cause of his reaction. Pt verbalized that he would not respond to the hospital with the paramedics and was encouraged to at least call someone to take him to the hospital.  This provider spoke with the patient?s mother and explained the events. The patient?s mother stated that the patient had febrile seizures when approximately 4 years old, associated with asthma exacerbations; but pt was evaluated with a neurologist and there were no abnormal findings. Pt admitted that he has a similar syncopal episode after washing a laceration and seeing his finger bleeding. Pt states this was a few years ago and witnessed by his father that told the patient he initially fainted and then became momentarily rigid before responding appropriately (similar to today?s events).   Ambulance - arrival @1536 report given and pt stated he was feeling better and declined further evaluation in truck and also declined transport to ED ( departed at 1545). Pt?s overall condition, appearance, including color was much improved. Pt denied any allergies or medication history. Past medical hx of febrile seizures at approximately age three and four, childhood asthma and one syncopal episode as an adult. Pt girlfriend  arrival and she agreed to drive patient from the vaccine clinic.  Pt and girlfriend were both provided with an explanation of the many concerning causes of syncope and the necessity for further evaluation in the Emergency department to rule out any underlying conditions. Both patient and girlfriend verbalized understanding and although they still declined to respond to ED directly from the clinic, both did agree to respond to ED if any changes in mental status occurred.  Pt lives alone, but agreed to stay with parents and family in order to have others watch him for any changes.  Pt was advised to followup with PCP and made aware that an  provider would contact him tomorrow to check on his status, understanding verbalized and agreed with plan of care.  Pt in no acute distress, awake, alert and oriented. Color within normal limits for  and departed facility with girlfriend at 15:56, steady gait noted.  Patient?s appointment for second dose was cancelled and will need to obtain clearance prior to second vaccine dose.
LAB_DATA: Vital signs and Blood glucose- 104 mg/dL taken on 3/29/20
HISTORY: hx of childhood asthma and febrile seizures at approximately age 4

SYMPTOM_TEXT: hospitalized/ "almost died"; ramsey hunt syndrome; Suffer shingles, including any all og its sequelae; Shingles; hearing loss; This spontaneous report as received from a nurse refers to a 65 years old male patient with no drug reactions/allergies. The medical history of the patient included cancer. The patient was vaccinated with a dose of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (Lot number reported as H0139009) (Lot number H0139009 is an invalid lot number for zoster vaccine live) subcutaneously on 13-NOV-2012. No concomitant medications were reported.   The nurse called stating the patient received zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) on 13-NOV-2012 developing Ramsey Hunt Syndrome and was hospitalized. The patient started to experience symptoms on 20-NOV-2012. The patient saw his primary care physician initially. He was also referred to an ENT (Ear, Nose and Throat) specialist on 07-DEC-2012. CT scan, lab work and spinal tab were performed without any results. However his symptoms exacerbated and he was hospitalized on 12-DEC-2012 and spent 3 to 4 days in the hospital. The patient was still experiencing deafness in one ear, trouble swallowing and partial paralysis of his throat. He was still recuperating at home. He was prescribed acyclovir for his condition. The patient had a history of cancer however he was in remission for the past year and had not received any therapy related to cancer in the past year. At the time of reporting, the outcome was reported as recovering.  Followup information has been received: all telephone attempts to obtain follow-up information have been unsuccessful.  Follow up information was received: nurse stated that she had received multiple calls from the safety department at least every week since she provided this report.  She had left voice mails for the safety department .She did not provide a better way to contact her. She stated that the patient still had a loss of hearing to the one side with paralysis and loss of sensation in one side of his throat; he had to be extremely careful when he eats, and his oncologist, informed the patient that if he could keep his weight at 190 pounds, he would not have to receive a feeding tube.  Nurse reported that the patient was under treatment for lymphoma and was in remission for at least a year prior to his receipt of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) and the subsequent development of his current difficulty as described above.  The patient was hospitalized.  Follow up information was received from the registered nurse concerning a patient. Demographics such a height and weight were updated. Current conditions of the patient included Penicillin (PCN) allergy, Allopurinol allergy and Uloric allergy post lymphoma-2 years. On 13-NOV-2012, at 15:20, the patient was vaccinated with a dose of Zoster Vaccine Live (ZOSTAVAX) (lot number and expiry date reported as H013944 and 25-OCT-2013 respectively) in the right arm at public health clinic or hospital. The patient experienced sore throat, processed over next 1-2 weeks then lost 20 pounds in 2 weeks due to vertigo, nausea/vomiting, double vision, loss of hearing in right ear. The patient eventually saw a physician at ENT, 2 weeks later, on 24-NOV-2012 (previously reported as 20-NOV-2012), the patient was diagnosed with Ramsay-Hunt syndrome. The event was considered to be life threatening and resulted in significant disability. Patient was hospitalized for 5 days. Then he saw an oncologist and was sent for admission to the hospital. He was admitted for further work up. At the time of vaccination patient was clear of recurrence of lymphoma. Outcome of the event was unknown (previously reported as recovering) and he was continued to have dysphagia. The patient required a medical intervention. No signed informed consent form was obtained.   Follow up information was received from the registered nurse stating that on an unknown date in December 2012 (reported as "Late December 2012") (previously reported as "13-NOV-2012") the patient was vaccinated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) On an unknown date in 2013 (reported as "Early 2013") the patient experienced hearing loss (medically significant) and also experienced he was hospitalized at an unspecified hospital on an unspecified date after receiving the zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) and the nurse reported that the patient "almost died" but did not (hospitalization and life threatening). The outcome of hospitalized/ "almost died" and hearing loss was unknown. The relationship between the events and zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) was not reported. SYMPTOM_TEXT: For BOTH initial (022621) and booster (032621) of Moderna, pt had moderate/severe eye reaction. Overnight about 3 days after first injection and 4 days after second injection.  Initial injection: pt went to bed on the 3rd night after vaccine having taken no medications and noted mild eye irritation. He woke up a few hours later (~midnight) to severe eye watering and blurriness which required him to keep his eyes closed with mild sinus congestion. No difficulty breathing noted. Pt had trouble getting it to stop despite taking loratadine 10mg and rinsing eyes with water. Pt seriously considered going to ER due to risk of blindness. Pt eventually fell asleep a few hours later and woke up with very sensitive eyes (irritated, very red) that took about 36h to fully recover.   Second injection: pt was on scheduled loratadine 10mg daily. Noted a similar eye irritation (this time four days after injection not three) when going to bed and took 50mg diphenhydramine (about 14h after loratadine dose). Woke up a few hours later to more minor but still debilitating eye watering with proportionally more sinus involvement. No difficulty breathing noted. Pt took an extended release pseudoephedrine, rinsed eyes with water  and waited for it to resolve about an hour or two later. Pt awoke the next morning to much less sensitive eyes than first time.   Note: due to first experience. From time of administration of second dose, pt was on scheduled naproxen (440mg loading dose followed by 220mg q12h), loratadine 10mg q24h,  and pseudoephedrine (120mg ER q24h). Pt took these scheduled days 1-3 and at time of second eye episode was only on scheduled loratadine still. Pt also had 50mg diphenhydramine on hand in case of episode.

I was very tired the night of 2nd vaccine, aside from that absolutely no side effects, hardly any arm pain, so all well.  I actually felt great for about 9 days.  Then on 3/22/21  I was suddenly awaken by an intense, and peculiar, bout of vertigo.  I am familiar with vertigo from ear infections in the past (last one about 15 years ago and the one prior about 22 years ago).  For me vertigo is a generally mild sensation that stays with me until it clears up.  This was, and is, much different, it ebbs and increases during the day, if I concentrate on a physical task it sort of diminishes, then comes back, at times it goes away completely for an hour or two then comes back strong.  At same time that this started my thoughts and mental acuity started to suffer kind of a "brain fog" is the best explanation I can give.  I also have a slight headache at the back of my head wrapping around to the temples, I don't know if I can link the headache to the brain fog since my neck often gives me trouble.  I have ruled out ear infection by purposefully spinning myself around to see if I would lose balance, did not affect my balance.  I can also walk a relatively straight line of about 20' with my eyes closed without stumbling.  It feels like a kind of vertigo, but much different than any I have experienced in past and much longer lasting.
LAB_DATA: I saw my General Practitioner yesterday, 3/29/21.  She ruled out high blood pressure, stroke, ear problems other obvious items.
HISTORY: slight elevated blood pressure as of 10/2020

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had a 9:15 am appointment, received the shot about 9:30 am. Shopped in store for 10-min and drove to run more errands. About 9:45 am driving, I noticed my face starting to numb on my right hand side beginning with my upper lip, around my nostril, cheek and jaw line. After an hour of numbness, I called my doctors office and spoke with a nurse. The nurse had not heard of these symptoms before and sent me to the local ER at the hospital. As we drove to the ER, I noticed my jaw muscles getting tighter, but not so over powering that it felt like it would lock up. While under observation for an an hour or so, a Physician?s Assistant did neurological exams as my symptoms looked like a potential mild stroke. I passed the exams and sent home to observe any changes. The morning of day two (today), I have strong flu like symptoms with chills, shivering, aching muscles and the skin on my back and neck have a pins and needles feeling. What?s more, I have a present ringing in my ears today.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received 2nd dose of Pfizer Series on 01/06/2021. That following Monday 01/11/2021 the patient noted a very red, raised whelp on the arm that they had received the vaccination. They also  noted a center or core in the middle of the whelp. This type of reaction was not noted with the first vaccine and the area was not present prior to the vaccine per the patient's report.  Since the whelp persisted for numerous days the patient reached out the medical colleges for advice. Eventually in late January she sought the opinion of a dermatologist since the area of concern had not improved. The dermatologist was unsure if this reaction was caused by the vaccine but did  prescribe steroids to help with redness/swelling. Despite steroids the area did not improve. On a repeat visit to the dermatologist in late February a tissue sample of the whelp was taken and sent off for analysis. The analysis returned back as squamous cell carcinoma.  The patient reports that after this finding a 1.2CM area was considered to be squamous cell carcinoma. The dermatologist removed the carcinoma and repeat samples have returned back showing clear margins.  The patient does not report having a diagnosis of squamous cell carcinoma in the past.

Her bed is 15' from her bed, and could not get back and forth and was stumbling and exhausted from that small distance.  She could not hold her head up, and had to stay in the bathroom to get enough energy to get back to the bed, and could not get her feet up to get back in the bed due to being winded and exhausted as well.  This went on for a couple of days.  She did not eat, but nothing was staying down.  She had chills, was wrapped up in quilts, cold, and her hips, knees and ankles felt like somebody was pulling her apart.  On Sunday she started to begin feeling better, was light sensitive, almost a migraine type headache, sensitive to sound, and lost track of time.  She is still having some of the symptoms, the worst has passed, but still feels disoriented, dizziness.  Her right arm has a buzzy feeling on the upper and lower arm, both hands are very swollen, the right more so than the left.  Her fingertips were going numb on her right arm, but not on the left where she got the vaccine.  She would have to rub them to get the feeling to come back.  She is very shaky very easily, and if she turns too fast she will get dizzy.  For the stomach she normally takes Pantoprazole and her roommate got her some generic Omeprazole which calmed her stomach down and has been finishing up that bottle, but it was still not feeling well.  She never ran any fever, but never runs a fever, and took her temp a few days ago was 97.8 which is normal for her.  She has called her doctor and then called her again yesterday and missed her return call and will speak with her today.

I slept mostly well.  I did wake up in the middle of the night with the 2 bones in my left foot were throbbing where the screws are.  It feels like anywhere I had severe inflammation or surgery, there were intense feelings of burning pain.

Moderate chills, turned into approximately 100 degree fever (felt like the fever is breaking), sweating, became dizzy, vision was spotty, and then fainted.  (Adverse event occurred after both doses. After receiving  1st dose (February 26) and 2nd dose (March 26).

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Morning after 1st dose of Pfizer vaccine for COVID-19 had itching on ankles, later that day itching on wrists, followed by hives on arms and legs. I called PCP, spoke with NP who advised Claritin in morning and Benadryl at night. I don't tolerate Benadryl, so advised Claritin twice a day was ok and to resume Claritin 1 day after 2nd vaccination.  Stopped Claritin after hives resolved, 3 days before second vaccination was scheduled. The day before second vaccination scheduled I developed watery blisters on the outside of right thigh. I kept appointment for 2nd Pfizer but advised at that time may have worse reaction after 2nd Pfizer and that I had up to 3 weeks more to get 2nd Pfizer if I chose to do so. I called PCP after returning home. Got callback from NP next morning. Advised not to take 2nd Pfizer and to wait before trying any other vaccine. I mentioned increase number of watery blisters and beginning of pain in thigh but this was not addressed.  I checked internet for symptoms and suspected Shingles, even though I had been vaccinated some years prior. The next day pain was worse. I called again and insisted on talking directly to PCP. Over the phone diagnosed as Shingles and confirmed via photos.
OTHER_MEDS: Diltiazem, Dorsolamide HCL, Vitamin D, Multivitamins
ALLERGIES: Shellfish, Mango, several antibiotics, Angiotensin II Receptor Antagonists

Medic on site working in the observation area witnessed patient in his car, slumped into the seat and not moving forward as expected per protocol of this drive through mass vaccination site.  Upon assessment by medics, the patient had very pale skin color, eyes were closed, but he was responsive to questions.  Patient was able to state that he had a history of syncope and that this is not an unusual response for him to needles.  Patient was able to place his vehicle in park and wait in place for about 15 minutes and until he recovered.  When fully recovered, patient traded seats with one of the other passengers in his vehicle and had one of the other passengers drive as they left the vaccination site.

I had hives after 1st Pfizer dose. 2 days before 2nd dose scheduled (hives had resolved) I started to get itchy spots on right thigh. The day before 2nd dose I had watery blisters on right thigh in two spots. I went for 2nd dose and was advised that it may cause an even more adverse reaction and that I had 3 additional weeks to get 2nd dose if I didn't get it that day. I decided not to get it and do more research. I called PCP and got a call back next morning from NP I had spoken to earlier about hives. Advised not to take 2nd dose and wait regarding another type (eg J&J). I mentioned about the blisters but it was not addressed. I researched blisters and suspected I had Shingles even though I'd had Shingles vaccine some years prior. The next day pain was worse and more blisters appeared. I called insisting to speak with PCP, who diagnosed Shinlges over the phone and confirmed via photos I sent. Prescribed Valacyclovir. Four days after initial dose of Valacyclovi r Shngles symptoms beginning to subside.
ALLERGIES: Shellfish, Mango, Benicar & other of that class, several antibiotics

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Is 17 weeks pregnant with her first child. I do not know her estimated date of delivery. She fainted approximately 5 minutes after receiving her vaccine and fell from a chair. She landed on her side face down, so we turned her face up so we could see her face. Her eyes were barely open, but she nodded her head the second time we asked if she could hear us. We took her blood pressure, and it was 107/71 with a heart rate of 85. EMS came, and she felt better, so she decided not to go with them. They asked her to stand up to sit back in the chair. When they left, she slowly progressed to walking around while talking on the phone with someone to come pick her up so she didn't have to drive herself. She told us this was the first time she had fainted in 3 years and the first time ever fainting due to a vaccine.

The patient took another 500mg of acetaminophen at 2pm, 200mg of ibuprofen at 3pm, and complained of a sensation of hypersensitivity and mild "burning" across the skin. About 8 hours after receiving the vaccine I began to develop a fever.  I understand that fever, muscle aches and head aches are possible side effects of vaccinations in general and this one in particular.  Since I had tested positive for antibodies for the third time just two weeks prior to receiving this first dose of Moderna I was anticipating some reactions similar to what I have heard people experiencing for their second shot.  What followed the initial onset of fever was the worst flu symptoms I have ever experienced in my 48 years.  Fever continued to increase reaching 103 if not higher at times and staying elevated at level for over 6 hours.  Chills to the point of convulsions.  Nausea and one time vomiting.  Fever dreams (mild hallucinations), profuse sweating, intense head aches.  Muscle aches I could barely tolerate that I felt over every inch of my body.  This continued until 10am the following morning when I took some advil and finally fell asleep to the point of being virtually unwakeable until 2:30pm.  Upon waking I was able to sit up and drink water but the muscle soreness and slight fever continued throughout the day (101 fever).   I was able to eat some toast that evening.  That night the fever returned but not as high as the previous night.  The sweating was still profuse throughout the night and the muscle aches continued  but to a lessor degree.  The following day the fever subsided though muscle soreness continued.  That evening I was able to sleep regularly and now today (three full days after vaccination) I am roughly back to myself.  I understand that reading this seems as if these symptoms fall in line with what is expected and understand to be the side effects of the vaccine.  I am here today to tell you that I thought I was dying.  I have never, ever felt so terrible ever.  It was ten times worse than having covid.  I cannot imagine  anyone who is not healthy and string making through that and I can not believe I am expected to do it again to complete my vaccination.
HISTORY: I do not have a history of ling-standing health or chronic health conditions.  However, I had Covid in March of 2020 with some lingering symptoms for months and often when run down or overtired will feel some symptoms similar to covid symptoms (lung tightness / shortness of breath).  I have tested positive for antibodies on three occasions with the latest being exactly 1 year from contracting Covid-9  (two weeks prior to receiving the vaccine).
ALLERGIES: Tree Fruit (Stone Fruit i.e. Cherries, Apples, Peaches, Plums)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Listed on previous screen. Visual issues. I had a mild version of this reaction to the first dose (1/22) and a more moderate reaction after the 2nd one (2/19). It was not listed on the side effects. I had visual issues of halo and flashing lights sporadically. After the first dose, only a few days. After the 2nd dose, 2 weeks solid. It is resolved now and I did not seek medical care. I had had surgery on both retinas over the last 5 years, so I am not sure if this exacerbated something in my eyes related to vascular dilation or something nerve related. It did only occur right after both doses (Moderna) and so I do believe it is somehow connected. That being said, it did not stop me from daily functioning and I do not at all regret the vaccine. Just wanted to tell someone.  Another friend reported similir visual issues and I encouraged him to report it as well.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approximately 30-45 minutes after consuming a dessert that had coconuts, I started having an allergic reaction. I started coughing and my lips started to swell mildly but this reaction didn't match the speed, severity, or overall symptoms of past experience with analyphylaxis to peanuts (which required 3 shots of epinephrine at urgentcare). After I realized I was having a reaction, it took another 45 minutes to get to a  to get and take benadryl (was on vacation at the time). I was lightheaded and lost my balance and while I wasn't personally concerned my friends urged me to go to the hospital to get checked out. I was given steroids in pill form and put under observation for about 3-4 hours then released with a prescription for an epipen and 5 days of steroids. Several days after this ordeal I had an endometriosis flare up (which I expected post vaccine) as well as migraines and mental fog that lasted for about a week. I also experienced significant hair fall that week as well.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received my first Moderna COVID-19 vaccine on 12/31/20 at hospital. after my first vaccination I noticed that I was experiencing tinnitus intermittently in both ears.  I received my second vaccination on 1/28/2021 at Hospital . At the beginning of February I noticed itching and some swelling and redness on my toes in both feet. I used over the counter lotrimen cream for two weeks with no improvement. I started using over the counter hydrocortisone cream which helped relieve the itching but the swelling was not improving and I developed red ulcers on my toes bilaterally and it became painful to walk. I went to an urgent care facility on 3/9. The physician at the urgent care facility expressed concern that I could have a vascular issue and referred me to a vascular surgeon. She also referred me to a podiatrist. She prescribed me a course of prednisone which I started on 3/10/2021 and completed.   I saw the vascular surgeon on 3/11/2021 and was diagnosed with Raynauds Disease. The MD informed me that I had the beginning stages of Gangrene on my toes and prescribed me nifendrine 30 mg extended release daily. I consulted with a podiatrist on 3/11/2020 who noted that she agreed the symptoms on my toes were vascular in nature. She stated she has seen an increase of patients seen with ulcers recently.   I am still experiencing intermittent tinnitus and still have symptoms in my toes that are better with medication, but not resolved.
LAB_DATA: Two diagnostic tests done at vascular surgeon office on 3/11/2021 - records pending. COVID 19 rapid test done at urgent care on 3/9/2021 with negative result

On Monday 3/15 or Tuesday 3/16 I started developing a rash on the knuckles of my right hand and fingers. It first looked like small burns, and then started swelling to look more like spider bites. The rash spread over the course of the next two weeks, and also showed up on my left hand. Eventually, the one on my right hand looked like a blood blister. The rashes itched at first, and then started hurting to the touch. They were especially sensitive to sunlight. Now, as of 3/30, they seem to be clearing up.

The vaccine site was Community Center being done by Paramedics and Fire Fighters. I received the vaccine and sat down in the chairs to wait the required 15 minutes. Within 2-3 minutes my face got very hot. I could feel the heat under my mask. Another minute or two, just below my knees to my toes started tingling. Another two minutes or so, I felt like my eyes were swelling. I took my glasses off and looked at my husband and asked if my eyes are swelling, he said, they sure are and called over one of the paramedics that were there. They directed me to a more private are and put me on a monitor and monitored my vital signs. My blood pressure which is well controlled on my meds (which I did take that morning) climbed and climbed to 200s/100s. My chest was tight and uncomfortable and getting more difficult to breath. They put and 02 mask on and gave me Benadryl IM. By that time the squad was there and took me to the local hospital ER. In the squad my tongue started to swell. At the hospital they gave me Solumedrol IV which took care of it all. The swelling quickly went away in my tongue and face, the chest pressure went away, and all the other little annoyances like the tingling. The hospital did a chest x-ray and bloodwork. I went home after 3-4 hours with a prescription for Prednisone 50 mg daily for 5 days.  No further reactions after that.
LAB_DATA: Chest x-ray and blood work. I was not given info on what labs were drawn or the results.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient presented on 3/30/21 for his first COVID vaccine appointment. Patient checked in at the pharmacy and came back to the clinic location. Patient was with his wife who confirmed that it has never been due to the medication but just a fear of needles. Patient gets lightheaded. After giving the vaccine, the patient was fine at first but then did state he wasnt feeling well. The wife, came and held his hands and I was holding his back and head. Patient did tense up and shook once (not a seizure) and did lose consciousness for about 10 seconds. Had a tech call a code white and store management did come. Patient came back to and seemed fine. He had a Gatorade and drank that and also a bottle of water. Patient started to feel a little better but had a second minor episode (did not seem to lose consciousness). We also got a cold pack and placed on patient's head/neck. He ultimately took about 45 mins to an hour post dose and was able to leave under his own power. Patient and wife appreciative of efforts.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I was directed to my seat (if walking into the room, the first table but the 2nd seat).  The woman was learning the computer system from a gentleman, and she assured me she just didn't know the computer, but knew how to give a shot.  I pulled my arm out of my sweatshirt and pushed my short sleeve shirt up.  She did the alcohol wipe, then pinched my arm, I looked away as the shot went in.  I felt a horrible pain...not even sure how to describe it, just extreme pain and very achy and said Ow maybe 3 times (I am one that can tolerate quite a bit of pain, and I assumed it would sting, but this was different) as she was injecting me.  She apologized. The gentleman said Johnson and Johnson is a little thicker.  I said to him that I had never ever experienced this much pain with a vaccine before-never.  Again, I am talking about as it was injected. I went to sit down for the waiting area, the gentleman who was handing out cards for reviews asked me about it and I said it hurt so bad, I'd never had a shot hurt that bad.  Another worker (female) overheard me and asked me if it was a burning-she had a burning with hers (think she said moderna). I said I would not necessarily say it was a burning, it was pain. As I sat there, I texted my husband and told him how bad it hurt (with the injection) and I've never had a vaccine hurt like that.  I started to wonder if it was administered incorrectly? I looked over and the gentleman was now doing the vaccines and she was watching. My husband had Pfizer and he said that didn't hurt at all. I was feeling it up into my neck as I was sitting there. I was trying to rub my arm and neck hoping that would help as well as move my arm around. When we could leave, I asked the volunteer if she had heard of anyone else having that much pain DURING the shot.  She said she only heard of maybe one other person that said ow. I left, started to cry in the car because of the pain and experience, then spoke with my husband before I left. I came home and got some ice to put on my arm hoping that would help. I did expect pain in the arm after a shot. Within a couple of hours, I noticed pain going down my arm and into my wrist. I thought maybe I needed to be active with my arm and move it so tried that.  I started to notice more side effects of the vaccine as the evening progressed:  I had the typical side effects I figured I'd have, achy, joint pain, chills, nauseous, no fever though. I was noticing pain into my neck (occasionally even into jaw), shoulder, scapula area of the back, and left side under the bottom part of my ribs.  I was feeling tightness in my chest, too, so I decided to try 2 aspirin to see if it helped with any symptoms. I did have slight dizziness, and a weird sensation in my head-like a zapping? I didn't sleep well, and had to stay completely off of my left side. Thursday, I felt better than that night, but still tired, achy, nauseous, chills, and not 100%.  My arm still was really affected...it seemed extremely fatigued as well as painful...the pain was radiating up and down and couldn't raise my arm without it hurting. Around noon I decided to take 2 aleve to see if that would help me at all. It did help with the pain and achiness, but was getting a "nerve-type" pain still up and down my left arm into neck/scapula area down to my wrist and hand/fingers. Still couldn't sleep on my left side. Friday, I was definitely doing better with all the other symptoms, I could abduct my arm more than 90 degrees, so I was excited about that. I did wake up with my middle/ring finger hurting (at the base of that area) and a bit numb so put my hand in and out of a fist. The pain subsided, but the numbness/tingling sensation was still there. I continued to take aleve hoping that maybe there was just inflammation around the nerve causing the issue.  Aleve did help, but it still never went away completely.  By late afternoon, I was getting concerned if I was permanently affected by this. As I was holding a bowl of food and eating, my left arm was going numb. I was even feeling it into my gluts (sciatica?). Again...all of this was after the shot and only on the side I received the shot. That evening I was able to lay on my left side, but not for long periods of time because it became uncomfortable and arm would go numb. Saturday, I still had the nerve pain and was not in a good spot.  It made me sad, angry, scared, and I didn't want to talk about it too much-just wanted my arm and all the different radiating pains I was having to be back to normal. I was feeling it up into my neck, scapula, my side(the rib area I previously mentioned), even into my gluts and down leg near ankle as well as down the arm into elbow, forearm, wrist, and hand, fingers (particularly that middle finger and thumb area).  I tried to use my arm as normally as possible thinking maybe I need to just keep it moving, but it would fatigue, especially between shoulder and neck. I tried Ibuprofen on this day.  Again, the pain relievers helped some, but didn't take it all away. Sunday I was in a horrible spot mentally and crying throughout the day because of the sensations I was feeling still: up and down the arm, shoulder, neck, scapula, side and still into ankle area. I decided I would call my doctor on Monday. Monday, I woke up and was feeling better overall, but still having the nerve sensations down my arm as well as up into shoulder, neck, scapula and my left side.  But everything was not as intense.  I spoke to my doctor who said there was a protocol, a number I needed to call.  Monday night I took ibuprofen because I started to have a horrible headache-didn't go away completely and still have this morning-not sure if it's related or just a normal headache. Still feeling tingling nerve sensations into forearm and fingers.  My shoulder/neck area feels fatigued, but so far not noticing the nerve pain yet, so that's a positive. On Monday,  it seemed to get worse as the day went on, so we will see. I definitely feel in hand/wrist/fingers as I am typing now. I know this is a lot, and I think I've captured it.  Again, I had none of this pre-shot.  The pain during injection is what alarmed me most as I expected side effects after the shot, but not this nerve type issue.  For this to be lasting as long as it is concerns me, and the fact that it exhibits on my left side where I got the shot. I am very anxious as it hasn't gotten back to normal.
LAB_DATA: I spoke to my doctor 3/29/21 and the person.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Reviewed.  3/23/2021 @ 10 am patient received Pfizer boost vaccination administered in  Provider Room.  Patient was monitored in waiting area for 15 minutes with no reported side effects.    At about 1:45 pm  patient was in waiting area and had just finished eating a sandwich with tomato when she started feeling SOB and itchy.  A rapid response was called and the patient was transported to the ED by wheelchair. Patient has documented allergy to tomatoes.  In ED patient and IV was started and the patient was medicated with methylprednisolone 125 mg x1 IVP, Diphenhydramine 25 mg IVP, Lorazepam 1 mg IVP and Famotidine 20 mg IVP.

Patient presented for Covid -19 vaccination based on the fact that he is a caregiver and qualifies under said rules. About 10 minutes into the 15 minute observation. Patient reported to the observer that he was having just a little bit of difficulty swallowing and felt a little warm. He denied shortness of breath, he was brought into the evaluation area. He was  mildly uncomfortable but was able to speak in full sentences, did not appear short of breath and was articulate and cooperative with the exam. Initial vitals revealed that his pulse is 122,O2 sat was 98%,  blood pressure was 220/120.( Denied known HTN) He had very mild wheezes bilaterally.(Denied H/O asthma or wheezes) He reported feeling warm. He asked for something to drink and after taking several sips stated that his swallowing felt a little bit better describe the situation that is the back of his throat but a little lower. Oral exam revealed slightly red and posterior pallet with chronically enlarged tonsils without exudate, neck is supple, no adenopathy. He was able to swallow without difficulties. He was warm. He was given a cold compress which he stated improved his symptoms. Reports he does not have underlying asthma, has not had such a reaction before and had not been ill in the preceding days,   patient was given a chewable Zyrtec. After approximately five minutes blood pressure was re-checked and it was 160/88 with a heart rate of 98 and O2 sat is 98 wheezes appeared to improve slightly but were persistent. Patient stated in general he was not feeling any better and feeling slightly worse BP was again noted to be 220/110. Concern was for an allergic reaction as demonstrated by the wheezes and sensation of difficulty swallowing but given his persistent significantly elevated blood pressure epi-was not indicated but emergent transport was. 911 had already been called for transport to the hospital for further evaluation.  EMS was transferred care. He was transported to the hospital. He was discharged several hours later.  Review of ER notes revealed he was hypertensive at 187/87 with a pulse of 95 ,he did not have any active wheezes or oral pharyngeal swelling on their exam. he was given a G.I. cocktail for his "itchy" throat. No specific conclusion was determined as to the cause of his reaction, other than a possible ?post injection inflammatory reaction? and was discharged to home without any other treatment required.  Was was transported back to the vaccination facility by private vehicle and appeared to be in good condition but tired according to the vehicles driver.   MD dictated on March 30, 2021
HISTORY: Depression, chronic pain, obstructive sleep apnea

On 09-MAR-2021, the patient was vaccinated with varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX) 0.5 milliliters, subcutaneous, lot number T022314, expiration date 30-JUN-2022 for vaccine series.        On 09-MAR-2021, the patient had a localized reaction. The reaction was severe and had to be treated with antibiotics. The reaction was a red swollen, hot to touch area on the left thigh, 4 cm wide that required medical attention (injection site reaction, vaccination site cellulitis, injection site warmth, injection site inflammation and injection site erythema). Caller reported she had been doing this for 30 years and had never seen anything like it. Caller reported the reaction was coming from a specific lot number of VARlVAX, and was sure was not the diluent because it had been used to reconstitute other vaccines and no such reactions had been seen.      The outcome of injection site reaction, vaccination site cellulitis, injection site warmth, injection site inflammation and injection site erythema was reported as not recovered. On 24Feb2021, prior to the onset of events, the patient received their second of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (batch number: unknown) via Intramuscular route for COVID-19 infection prophylaxis.  On 24Feb2021, 30 minutes after receiving the vaccine, patient started speaking and gibberish came out. The patient stated that she could not form words. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient presented to the emergency department early March 28, 2021 after experiencing 5-7 hours of chest pain. The chest started when the patient went to bed the evening of March 27, where he began having substernal non-radiating chest pain with inspiration. The pain was relieved by sitting upright and by taking some acetaminophen. He received his 2nd dose of the Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine on March 25 (first dose was March 5). He was initially treated with ketorolac 15mg IV and given 1 liter of lactated ringer's solution via IV.  His chest pain resolved after this. He was eventually given colchicine 0.6mg twice daily and ibuprofen 600mg 3 times daily due to concern for myopericarditis. He was ultimately found to have no evidence of pericarditis after undergoing a cardiac MRI, thus colchicine and ibuprofen were discontinued. Due to findings of mildly reduced ejection fraction on imaging, he was started on metoprolol XL 25mg once daily at discharge.
LAB_DATA: EKG 3/28/21: sinus tachycardia (rate 107 bpm), ST elevation, probably due to early repolarization EKG 3/29/21: normal sinus rhythm, nonspecific T wave abnormality  C-reactive protein 3/28/21: 46.9mg/L (ref. range <9 mg/L) ESR 3/28/21: 9 mm/hr (ref. range <15 mm/hr) D-dimer 3/28/21: 0.42 ug/mL (ref. range <0.50) High sensitivity troponins 3/28/21: 148 ng/L (time 02:45) -> 114 ng/L (time 05:45) (ref. range <19 ng/L) WBC 11.27 k/uL (ref. range 3.7-10.3)  Cardiac MRI 3/29/21:  1. Normal sized left ventricle with mildly reduced global systolic  function (EF 47%).  2. Normal sized right ventricle with mildly reduced global systolic  function (EF 46%). 3. No significant valvular abnormalities. 4. There is no significant late gadolinium enhancement.

1/12 vaccination About 4-5 hours later, I started feeling like I was going to black out; tightness in my chest. Could see little black dots. I pulled over as I was driving. I got off the interstate and was on the phone with my daughter. She told me to call 911, I put my head down and laid down. The ambulance got there, my daughter was there, and they could feel the skipping of beats. My BP was up, my HR was irregular. I still had the tightness in my chest. The medic said I am going to give you some nitro to see if would help with the tightness. I felt like I was going to black out. Arrhythmia was noticed on the monitor; EMT gave me a jolt of  and it immediately stopped the dysrhythmia. Transported to ER, inpatient overnight. Medical team decided I could go home, set up with follow up appt. Put me on a echo, stress test, HR monitor for a month (caught one episode and it lasted 1 hour in the middle of the night).  *i feel better but once in a while I get the lightheadedness and can feel the skipping.
HISTORY: hypertension, afib, seasonal allergies with asthma

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After the second dose of Moderna on 3/20/21 I experienced the expected low grade fever, body aches and chills on Saturday 3/21. The entire week following I had felt exhausted and had GI upset. Thurs day afternoon 3/25 I started to experience some dizziness which was out of the norm for me. On Friday 3/26 I woke up, unable to sit up or stand up without falling over and getting extremely nauseated. Everything was spinning and the only thing I could do was lay down. I took .5mg Ativan and 25mg Meclazine with no effect. After 4 hours of laying down, crawling to the bathroom and kitchen to get some food in, I ended up throwing up. My doctor suggested I go to the ER which I did around 2:45-3pm. I was admitted, an EKG was administered and a CAT scan. I was given IV fluids and 1mg Ativan and more Meclazine. My Vitals were WNL and no issues found iht EKG or CAT scan. I was d/c home around 8pm. I have not experienced any vertigo since but severe anxiety around it.  I believe this was caused by the vaccine as I have never experienced anything this severe before.
LAB_DATA: EKG - 3/26/21 - no adverse result CAT scan- 3/26/21- no adverse result

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Per clinical pharmacist internal report:   Adverse Drug Reaction Vaccine: COVID vaccine (unclear if 1st or 2nd and which manufacturer) Reaction: Unclear if associated with vaccine but wanted to report in case it is  Patient presented to hospital via EMS with a CC of dizziness and nausea. She was found to have increase O2 demands (4L O2, 3L O2 at home) but was ready for discharge when she developed aphasia, bilateral grip weakness, and staring into space. Oxygen was increased to 10L and a Code Stroke was called. Subsequent workup was negative for a stroke (MRI, CT). The following day, another episode occurred and MRI did show an acute left frontal stroke determined to be embolic in nature per neurology in a patient with a below goal INR and atrial fibrillation.  The patient has a past medical history of atrial fibrillation (CHADS VASC 5 prior to CVA this admission) and is on warfarin at home. INR at admission was 1.79 (previously stable with home regimen per hospital ACC notes, no missed doses were noted PTA). Due to NPO status, the patient was soon placed on full-dose enoxaparin at 0346 on 3/11 when admitted. This was continued and no doses were missed prior to CVA being diagnosed. The patient's husband states that she was in normal health until her COVID vaccine the morning of admission.  Unclear if COVID vaccine could have decreased INR or put patient at a higher clot risk. Of note she was found to have Ulceration and infection of left 2nd toe however systemically she was not exhibiting signs of infection.  Pfizer COVID-19 Vaccine - lot number: EN6199  Given at hospital on 03/10/2021

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pfizer vaccine- 1st dose Lot EN6199 administered 3/23/2021 at 11am. Patient began feeling nauseous and very lightheaded 10 minutes post-vaccine. She agreed to be evaluated in the ED. Clinic staff took patient to ED for evaluation.   Reviewed by Risk, in review  of the EMR ED MDM Provider notes on 3/23/21 @ 11:13am;   "Patient was seen by myself and staffed Dr. who also saw the patient here in the ED. Patient is a 90-year-old female past medical history of CLL who presents to the emergency department today with concerns for nausea mild lightheadedness and generalized weakness after receiving her 1st COVID vaccine this morning 15 minutes prior to arrival. On exam she is afebrile nontoxic appearing she is in no acute distress. CBC with differential revealed leukocytosis with a white blood cell count of 69.6. This is just slightly increased when compared to September 2020, WBC 62.7 at that time. H&H stable. Platelets stable. No bandemia noted. Suspect this is due to her CLL. BMP revealed initially elevated potassium with a K of 5.3 this was repeated 3.9, suspect that the initial potassium was hemolyzed. Urine dipstick negative for nitrites and blood, small leukocytes noted. Urine culture pending.   Chest x-ray revealedpatchy left basilar atelectasis and/or scarring, decreased since previous exam. Severe degenerative changes left shoulder, moderately severe degenerative changes right shoulder; somewhat increased since previous exam.   Patient was given Zofran here in the ED. I suspect her symptoms related to recent COVID vaccine. She will be discharged home with Zofran as needed for nausea. Recommend she have close follow-up with her PCP. She is encouraged to return to the ED immediately with any new or worsening concerns. Stable at discharge."

She lay on the ground with her feet up until the FD arrived.  Listening to her interview by the fire dept, it was discovered that she normally suffers from epilepsy and probably had a small seizure.  She wasn't able to remember everything but she was coherent and able to answer most other questions.  Her blood pressure was elevated and slowly came down as they monitored her.  Her boyfriend and son were also present and the fire dept released her to their care after seeing her blood pressure come down closer to normal and seeing her able to stand and walk.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Headache at first mild and very flush within 30 minutes of shot then severe and constant upon awaking in the morning. Fever 101.5-100.8 all day.  Fatigue , body aches, lower back pain. Sharp pain in left leg.

Headache began around 8:30 PM and went from my temples and forehead to the base of my neck, followed a while later by pain in both arms between my shoulders and elbows.  Knowing sleep would be difficult, I stayed up until 2:00 AM and fell asleep about 3:00 AM.  I awoke at 3:20 AM trembling so badly that I couldn't hold a thermometer in my mouth.  So, it was time for "chills and fever" and I put sweat pants and a sweat shirt over my flannel Pjs, heavy socks on my feet, and socks on my hands.  My entire body felt ice cold.  Back under the covers, I finally warmed up and slept off and on for almost eight hours.Woke up around noon on Saturday, feverish, feeling nauseous, exhausted, and still feeling the headache and arm pains.  My "normal" temperature runs from 97.1 to 97.6, but ranged from 100.2 to 100.5 for two days after the vaccine.  Slept off and on around the clock on Saturday and Sunday, and by Monday the headache, pain, and fever were gone.  Slight nausea remained as well as the fatigue on Monday.  On Tuesday, my legs felt wobbly, like "sea legs."  By Wednesday, I was back to normal catching up on email and reading my books, and on Thursday drove out to the county to bring food to my sister and fix her PC.  I understand that seniors do not usually get the side effects as I did, because the immune system declines with age.  Apparently, my immune system is not aware of my birth date.  Can't help but wonder if taking Co-Q-10, as I've done for almost twenty-four years, has anything to do with it.
LAB_DATA: None.  I didn't even take an aspirin.  I was happy the vaccine was working, but am now curious as to why "I" am the only senior citizen I know who had such side effects.
OTHER_MEDS: Fishoil Pills, B Complex, D3, and Co-Q-10

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had seizures as a child but was not diagnosed. In 2018, I had two seizures, but was diagnosed and have been on 100mg zonisamide for 2.5 years with no episodes. In 2014, I had a bad fever during an infection, and may have seized while sleeping. Not sure. In my adult life, I have received annual flu shots every year, and twice developed fevers as a side effect. After Moderna #2, I woke at 1:30am at my apartment with chills and fever. Took 2 acetaminophen and used the bathroom. I seized before I could take my temp. Upon reviving, I noted that about 15 minutes had elapsed since I first woke, so this seizure lasted under 10 minutes. I had a bruise on the back of my head, and later developed some bruising on the front of my thigh from the fall. I followed the protocol that my neurologist has established for me: called my sister for a ride to ER for evaluation. After several tests, I was released to my sister's care. Precautions we took for the next 24 hrs at sister's home: take temp every 2-3 hours to watch for fever, take acetaminophen every 6 hours. I'm fine now.
LAB_DATA: 3.26.21 ECG 3.26.21 CAT Scan of head 3.26.21 metabolic panel, etc
OTHER_MEDS: Zonisamide 100mg once per day; Lisinopril 5mg once per day; Travaprost .004% one drop in each eye once per day; multivitamin

Incident occurred at Health Department mobile clinic hosted by County Public Health at County Fairgrounds. The clinic was staffed by Health Department staff, County Public Health volunteers, County Fire Department Paramedics and contract temp staff. Client received his first dose of Pfizer vaccine (lot #: EP6955 exp: 6/30/21) and was advised to wait in the waiting area for 15 minutes for recovery. During the recovery period, about 10 minutes post-vaccine, client was seated and reported to the monitoring paramedic that he felt "dizzy and might faint" and moved onto his knees. The paramedic immediately attended to the client and caught him as he fainted. The paramedic slowly brought the client to the ground in a supine position. A second parmedic called for an ambulance and Health Department RN also responded at 4:45pm. The client immediately regained consciousness. The client was alert and oriented. The client reported that he has never before fainted or had problems with vaccine administration. The client was returned to a seated position and provided juice and water.  EMS arrived with ambulance at 4:55pm, they conducted their assessment and were concerned about 'abnormal heart rhythms' found via EKG. Client reported no cardiac hx. They offered to transport the client to Hospital for further evaluation. The client accepted the transport. The client left County Fairgrounds via ambulance at 5:16pm.

On this day it stayed around the same, I did draw a pen mark around it and the rash grew a few more centimeters.  The third day (March 25th), it was now the biggest it had been but the middle of the rash started to clear up.  It looked like there was a red ring/oval around the rash.  By Thursday night, the redness has started to clear up.   Friday, March 26th, the rash was almost gone, but I had an itchy rash on my face. She got the vaccine, had no reactions. On 3/6/21 she had blurred vision and being a little confused.  On the 8th when he returned back from work and she took her blood sugar which was 579.  So he rushed her immediately to urgent Care, they checked her blood sugar and there was no reading, and they sent her to Hospital.  In the ER at the hospital it was 408.  They gave her insulin, stabilized her and they told her to check with her doctor.  She consulted with her physician the next day and they put her on Metformin, which did not bring the blood sugar down at all.  On 3/10/21 he took her back to the ER again and they stabilized her again and did more testing to rule out any stroke or anything else, but also informed her that the vaccine pushed her over the pre-diabetic stage to being a diabetic.   She went back to the doctor again who increased her Metformin on 3/16/21, and her levels are still not within acceptable range but better than 300-400, but are in the 200+ ranges.   She is very dizzy, weak for the last 3 weeks and her vision is blurry as well, and she is not able to work as a nurse due to these reactions.   She does have a doctors note that she can return to work tomorrow without restrictions.  Her blood pressure was extremely high as well, and her physician increased her medicine.
LAB_DATA: EKG to rule out stroke.  Lab work was unremarkable except for the blood sugars.   The PCP has that information.
PRIOR_VAX: Flu vaccine, more than 4 years ago.  PCP has information.
